  "body": "## Description\r\n\r\nThe Discover view has a search function at the top of the view. This function replaces the header but the action can be cancelled without reverting back to the original header. Furthermore, to cancel the search action you click a back arrow that becomes confusing due to this indeterminate state.\r\n\r\n## Reproduction\r\n\r\n[iOS]\r\n\r\n1. Go to Discover view.\r\n2. Tap Search icon to reveal `Type your search tags here`\r\n3. Observe keyboard slides up with cursor focused on input.\r\n4. Tap the Discover view avoiding the header.\r\n5. Observe keyboard slides down with search form still visible.\r\n6. Tap the back arrow to return to the normal header.\r\n7. Tap the same spot a second time to reveal the flyout sidebar menu.\r\n\r\n### Scenario variation\r\n\r\n1. With the search input in focus type some text but do not hit return.\r\n2. Tap the Discover view avoiding the header.\r\n3. Observe that what appears to be a searched term is an unfinished search input action.\r\n\r\n## Expectation\r\n\r\n* Cancelling the keyboard action should revert the header back to normal and cancel any incomplete searches. \r\n* It's unclear to me in this situation whether you should type search terms then press the return on keyboard or press the magnifying glass icon. As the icon does nothing, the user is left to assume. Consider making the magnifying glass a submit button for an active search input form.\r\n* The back arrow to cancel the search action is acceptable only if the rest of these issues are met. As it is, the header appears broken from within this state.",
